	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99003345742075><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=5902&mid=99003345742075>It's a question of fairness</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=5902&mid=99003345742075#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, May 16th 1:17 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.64]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Loot really does two things - it makes one character stronger, and is a morale boost. As background for how an item like this is awarded, let me describe the loot systems of the two guilds that have killed Koi'Doken, the guy who drops this: Afterlife on Mithaniel Marr, and Fires of Heaven on Veeshan. Afterlife uses an elaborate and very interesting point system. The gist of it is this - you attend raids, and get points. You then spend points on items, and the person who has the most points overall gets to 'buy' it. Now, the interesting thing is in a case like this, monks or casters are more likely to have seniority - there's less items out there they'd be likely to buy, so if an item -is- better for them than for other classes, in all liklihood they'd have the most desire and the most points. So the system works. Now, FoH is very different. The leader decides who is the most deserving and could use it most, and he just decides that person loots. This item hasn't dropped yet for them, but it wouldn't be a big stretch to think this might go to one of their primary monks. The only thing that really makes this tough to call is the +sta, which helps out high HP tanks more than other classes. In the end, both systems are seniority-based and need based, but it's more likely an item would go to whomever could use it -most-.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
